00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:30.157
PROFESSOR: OK, so
welcome back everyone.

00:00:30.157 --> 00:00:32.240
This is going to be the
first class we're actually

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:34.944
talking about poker strategy, so
this should be pretty exciting.

00:00:34.944 --> 00:00:37.360
So the first thing we're going
to learn about is position,

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:39.560
and this is only
three slides long.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:42.391
So positions have
different names.

00:00:42.391 --> 00:00:43.890
They're put in two
different groups,

00:00:43.890 --> 00:00:45.800
and a lot of how
we describe what's

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:47.270
going in a particular
hand is going

00:00:47.270 --> 00:00:49.211
to be relevant to where
people are sitting.

00:00:49.211 --> 00:00:49.710
Why?

00:00:49.710 --> 00:00:51.210
Because people in
a late position

00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:53.940
get to act after people
in an early position.

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:55.700
And in general, the
positions are broken

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:58.010
into four different groups.

00:00:58.010 --> 00:01:00.370
There are the blinds,
who pay the blinds

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:03.870
and are first act on every
street after a pre-flop.

00:01:03.870 --> 00:01:05.645
There's early position,
middle position,

00:01:05.645 --> 00:01:10.080
and late position, where all
these positions have names,

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:12.680
except middle position.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:15.150
Starting in the big blind,
we call it under the gun,

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:17.840
under the gun plus 1,
under the gun plus 2.

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:22.030
You could also describe
these as seat 1, 2, 3, 4

00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:24.560
all the way to 9 or 10,
although I don't really

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:27.820
like that because I they all
have pretty unique names,

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:31.160
and they're descriptive
enough to just use those.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:35.010
So middle position is labeled
one, two, and three, and then

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:37.410
around the button you
describe their relation

00:01:37.410 --> 00:01:39.680
to the button, where
either you are the button

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:41.670
or you are cutting
off the button.

00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:44.640
And then some people get a
little crazy by calling this

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:48.770
the hijack, but I
tend to not do that,

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:50.360
and then as we
eliminate people, we

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:52.710
get rid of the least
interesting positions

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:55.970
to only keep the
ones with real names.

00:01:55.970 --> 00:01:59.290
So the reason that I'm
telling you this now

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:01.500
is we're going to be
going through hands

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:05.200
where I talk about
players by their position.

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.140
The individual person
doesn't matter,

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:08.600
but it's much to
understand what's

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:11.410
going on when I refer to them
as a cut off, or the button,

00:02:11.410 --> 00:02:12.260
or whatever.

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:14.460
But in general,
the later position

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:17.380
is better because you
get more information.

00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:20.670
You get to see people
acting before you.

00:02:20.670 --> 00:02:27.120
And as a result, the
money flows, in general,

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:28.150
to the late positions.

00:02:30.795 --> 00:02:32.420
The hand that you're
the button, you're

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:34.290
going to make the
most amount of money,

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:36.230
and you can see that
in poker tracker.

00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:38.620
And if you're losing
money on the button,

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:40.380
you should seriously
reevaluate how

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:42.213
you're playing that,
because that's when you

00:02:42.213 --> 00:02:44.180
make the most amount of money.

00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:46.610
Big blinds are an
interesting situation

00:02:46.610 --> 00:02:49.050
because they get to see
the flop for a discount,

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:53.344
because they're compelled
to pay some sort of bet.

00:02:53.344 --> 00:02:55.510
So you might think the
blinds are in a good position

00:02:55.510 --> 00:02:57.620
because they get a free
flop, but they're actually

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.540
in a terrible position because
when position matters post flop

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.970
they are the first to act
in every single situation.

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:05.720
So even though you
might think that you're

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:07.760
getting a discount for
being in the blinds,

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:09.522
you're getting a
discount and entry

00:03:09.522 --> 00:03:11.480
into a hand where you're
almost certainly going

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:15.400
to be at a major
informational disadvantage.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:19.390
However, interestingly,
in short stack situations,

00:03:19.390 --> 00:03:21.890
early position is
actually better

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:25.930
because you have the
opportunity to go

00:03:25.930 --> 00:03:28.700
all in before the
other person does,

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:33.680
and you maintain the equity from
aggression, the fold equity,

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:35.160
which we'll talk about later.

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:39.096
It's sort of like a
game of chicken where--

00:03:39.096 --> 00:03:41.910
so chicken is a game where
two people drive at each other

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:45.860
until one person turns, where
it's like the an infinitely bad

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:51.720
return if they both don't turn,
and then one wins if one turns

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:52.820
and one doesn't.

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:54.800
So the proper
strategy in chicken

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:58.650
is to throw your steering
wheel out the window

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:00.680
so the other person
knows he only

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:04.380
has one option if he doesn't
want an infinitely big loss.

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:06.620
So with position, it works
very similar to that,

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:09.610
where if you're in a tournament
where neither person wants

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:12.250
to see a showdown,
neither person wants

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:15.540
to deal with a coin flip
for their tournament life,

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:18.649
if you're in early position,
you have the opportunity

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:20.850
to be the aggressor
and go all in.

00:04:20.850 --> 00:04:22.930
So you get to discourage
the other person

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:24.770
from entering into it.

00:04:24.770 --> 00:04:27.550
So let's move on to
some basic concepts.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:31.200
So a lot of these things
are based on odds.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:33.800
So poker is a statistical
game, and we're

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:38.210
going to be talking about
applications of math to poker.

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:42.040
So why does drawing matter?

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:45.920
So drawing means you're
trying to make a hand.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:47.930
More cards that will
come out will give you

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:50.900
a really good hand, whereas
you don't necessarily

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:53.060
have a good hand right now.

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:55.550
In a really common
situation, there's

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.370
one guy that has an
OK hand, and there's

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:00.580
one guy that has nothing
but the potential

00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:03.350
to have a really good hand.

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:05.520
Most of the decision
points come down

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:09.830
to whether the guy with
nothing has equity,

00:05:09.830 --> 00:05:13.260
has an interest in
making his real hand.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:15.370
So really common
examples of these

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:17.980
are one person has
a pair or two pair,

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:21.190
and one guy has a
straight or a flush draw.

00:05:21.190 --> 00:05:23.690
If we're talking pre-flop,
someone has a pocket pair,

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:25.971
and someone else has
literally anything else,

00:05:25.971 --> 00:05:28.220
and they're trying to make
anything more than whatever

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:29.240
that guy's pairs is.

00:05:32.217 --> 00:05:33.800
So what the drawer
has to to-- the guy

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:36.530
without a real hand-- is
to decide whether the bet

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:39.550
he is facing or whatever
has to pay to see more cards

00:05:39.550 --> 00:05:44.090
to find out if he makes
his hand is worth the cost,

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:49.130
is worth what the
aggressor is making him pay

00:05:49.130 --> 00:05:51.110
to see that additional card.

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:56.000
And the person who has a
hand already wants to make it

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.130
so that the drawer cannot see
his card for a positive equity.

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:04.630
He wants to bet so much that
a call is bad, because that's

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:07.020
where his equity comes from.

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:10.760
So he can either bet enough so
that he folds-- the other guy

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:15.510
folds-- or bet enough that he'll
call and make a huge mistake.

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:18.560
Both are equally good.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:20.752
Actually the second
is probably better.

00:06:20.752 --> 00:06:22.910
AUDIENCE: You're
saying [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:22.910 --> 00:06:25.030
PROFESSOR: So I'm saying
a drawer is someone

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:28.120
who has a flush draw
or a straight draw,

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:31.280
or basically has no
real hand at showdown,

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:35.430
but has a reasonable chance
of, as more cards come out,

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:39.034
making a monster hand, like
making a hand which will almost

00:06:39.034 --> 00:06:40.200
certainly win that showdown.

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:45.535
OK, so let's go
through a scenario.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:00.840
OK, so this seems
pretty straightforward.

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:02.280
There's some sort
of bet pre-flop.

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:05.240
I called, and it was heads up.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:08.800
It came with four to a flush,
four hearts, and this guy bet

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:09.550
into me.

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:13.860
And the question
is, what do we do?

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.240
That's a big question.

00:07:15.240 --> 00:07:17.060
And I'm going to be
using this format a lot

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.600
because it's easier
to-- at least for me,

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:22.770
it's easier to see, and then
hopefully it's something

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:24.220
you guys will pick up on.

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:26.229
I'm only going to include
relevant information,

00:07:26.229 --> 00:07:27.770
and the cases are
going to be written

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:30.610
this format where we have
the relevant stacks up here.

00:07:30.610 --> 00:07:31.600
Here are the blinds.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:34.730
This means that small blind
is $20, big blind is $40,

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:36.260
and there's a $10 ante.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:38.250
This is a pot before
anyone does anything.

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:40.010
This is a pot as of a flop.

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:40.960
These are my cards.

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:43.240
The hero is whoever
we care about.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:45.930
The villain is the other guy.

00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:48.090
And this just shows the
order of what happens.

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:51.850
So here he raised
to $120 pre-flop.

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:52.840
Three big blinds.

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:54.120
I call.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:56.250
The flop comes eight of
hearts, three of hearts,

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:57.840
something that doesn't matter.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:00.000
He bets $370, all in.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.910
So my decision is,
what can I do here?

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:04.960
And this is a really
common scenario.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:06.600
And what we can do
is develop the tools

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:09.130
that we need to make
this-- to figure out

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:11.100
what we want to do here.

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:13.180
And rather than
should we call, we

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:15.950
can come up with a much
more resilient answer.

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:19.402
What's the biggest
bet that we can call?

00:08:19.402 --> 00:08:21.110
And we're going to
end up with a solution

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:23.810
set of this, of this area here.

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:26.330
That's what we
want to figure out.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.120
But first we need
to develop something

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:30.650
called expected value.

00:08:30.650 --> 00:08:34.240
So expected value is the same
in poker as it is in math.

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:36.169
It's just a probability
weighted average

00:08:36.169 --> 00:08:38.380
of all possible results.

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:41.169
So it's win percentage
times win amount minus

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:45.520
lose percentage
times lose amount.

00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:48.580
So in our scenario, we're going
to add some variables into it.

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:51.380
We're facing about
into a pot of 380.

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:55.030
Our EV is going to
be whatever chance

00:08:55.030 --> 00:09:00.220
we have to win times a pot of
380 plus whatever the be is,

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:05.140
x, minus our lose percentage,
which is 1 minus win percentage

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:07.160
times that same variable x.

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:11.220
And our threshold for
call is when EV equals 0.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:15.570
So pot odds is generally
what we call the relationship

00:09:15.570 --> 00:09:18.880
between the size of
the bet you're facing

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:23.100
and the pot that you would
win if you call that bet

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:24.950
and then win the hand.

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:28.050
So this is going
to be the equation.

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:30.140
So it's plus EV.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:34.650
It's positive expectation if
the chance you have of winning

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:39.470
is greater than the call amount
divided by the size of the pot

00:09:39.470 --> 00:09:40.950
after the call.

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:43.550
So say that we're
seeing a bet of $100.

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:46.050
We were seeing a bet a little
bit bigger than that, but just

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.390
for example purposes,
we'll use $100.

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:51.490
So your pot odds
would be $100 divided

00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:55.180
by $580, where $580 is
whatever was in the pot

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:58.310
before plus his
bet plus your call.

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:02.050
You'll win $580 if
you win this hand.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:07.250
So your call is
contributing 17% of the pot.

00:10:07.250 --> 00:10:09.020
And just so you
guys know, people

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:10.550
use pot odds in a different way.

00:10:10.550 --> 00:10:16.330
They talk about 1 to 4 and
use a different notation

00:10:16.330 --> 00:10:18.172
for referring to your
chance of winning.

00:10:18.172 --> 00:10:19.880
I always thought this
was very intuitive,

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:21.921
so that's what I'm going
to be teaching you guys.

00:10:21.921 --> 00:10:25.260
It's a percentage of the
pot that you can contribute.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:28.370
So if your win percentage
is more than 17%,

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:30.900
this is a plus EV call,
and this should be fairly

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:33.810
easy to wrap your head around.

00:10:33.810 --> 00:10:35.910
And your win percentage
can just be calculated

00:10:35.910 --> 00:10:38.790
based on what cards will
make you win divided by what

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:41.370
cards are left in the deck.

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:42.530
And those are called outs.

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:46.370
Cards that result in a win for
you based on your best estimate

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:48.350
are called an out.

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:52.150
So when you're going for a
flush-- so there are 13 hearts.

00:10:52.150 --> 00:10:53.770
You already know
about four of them.

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:55.800
They're either in your
hand or on the board.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:57.540
There are nine
hearts left that you

00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:01.305
could hit to make your
flush and presumably win.

00:11:01.305 --> 00:11:03.430
So your win percentage--
this is calculating it out

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:08.490
exactly-- is just 1 minus your
chance of hitting the flush

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:09.970
on either one of those cards.

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:12.715
So it's 40 out of
49 times 39 out

00:11:12.715 --> 00:11:16.110
of 48, which is
about equal to 34%.

00:11:16.110 --> 00:11:21.070
So since this 34%, our chance
of winning, is more than 17%,

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:23.410
the proportion of a call
that we're contributing,

00:11:23.410 --> 00:11:24.570
this makes it a good call.

00:11:24.570 --> 00:11:27.390
And the fact that this is
really big compared to this

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:29.240
makes it a really good call.

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.520
So this is how I think of it
in terms of visualizing it.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:38.370
So this whole pie
is the $580 pot

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:40.330
that it would be if you called.

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:43.970
This chunk is your 34% pot odds.

00:11:43.970 --> 00:11:47.230
Now, this chunk can be
comprised of the size

00:11:47.230 --> 00:11:49.890
of the bet you're
calling and your expected

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:51.250
value from calling.

00:11:51.250 --> 00:11:56.830
So here, the size of the chunk
is $197, which was 34% of $580.

00:11:56.830 --> 00:11:58.960
We can contribute
up to that amount.

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:01.080
If we get to
contribute less of it,

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:03.420
that means that any
additional chunk is EV.

00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:07.450
We are making $97
for making this call.

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:09.520
Similarly, if we make
a call that's too big,

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:12.120
we end up with a negative
chunk of that pie.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:15.990
So I'm teaching you a
quick rule for calculating

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:19.130
your chance of winning any
hand, and the quick rule

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:22.097
I'm going to use
is by Phil Gordon.

00:12:22.097 --> 00:12:23.430
So let's talk about Phil Gordon.

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:26.630
So Phil Gordon got-- he
seems like an OK guy.

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:28.460
He got fourth place
in the main event.

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:30.440
He won a World Poker tour.

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:32.400
He won two British
championships.

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:34.330
He's the head referee
of the World Series

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:35.555
of rock, paper, scissors.

00:12:35.555 --> 00:12:37.430
These guys get into
really interesting things

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.560
when they're not playing
poker, and he's the author Phil

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:41.860
Gordon's Little Green Book.

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:44.550
So Phil Gordon invented
this thing which

00:12:44.550 --> 00:12:47.340
caught on called Gordon's
rule of two and four,

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:50.350
which basically just
says each of your outs

00:12:50.350 --> 00:12:54.130
is worth 2% for
each additional card

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:56.090
you get to see for
that side of the bet.

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:58.670
And it should be fairly
obvious where 2% comes from.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:00.880
It's just 1 divided
by 50, and it's

00:13:00.880 --> 00:13:05.920
a rough estimate of what each
out is worth over 49, or 48,

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:08.660
or however many cards are left.

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:12.010
If you get to see both the
turn and the river, you use 4%,

00:13:12.010 --> 00:13:14.215
and that's the whole role.

00:13:14.215 --> 00:13:15.840
I'm sure someone
figured it out before,

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:17.631
but he was nice enough
to coin it and write

00:13:17.631 --> 00:13:20.950
in his book, which is why
I'm giving him credit for it.

00:13:20.950 --> 00:13:24.064
So some examples of these
are if you have a low pair

00:13:24.064 --> 00:13:25.730
and you're trying to
get three of a kind

00:13:25.730 --> 00:13:28.574
by the turn or the
river, you have two outs.

00:13:28.574 --> 00:13:29.990
And if you're
trying to figure out

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:33.280
your chance of making that
three of a kind on the turn,

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:38.970
you do two outs times 2% for a
total of 4% to make your hand.

00:13:38.970 --> 00:13:41.450
Simple enough.

00:13:41.450 --> 00:13:43.220
Other common examples
are flush draw,

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:46.350
which should be nine outs
to give you odds of 9

00:13:46.350 --> 00:13:49.810
divided by 47, or about 18%.

00:13:49.810 --> 00:13:51.750
An inside straight
draw is four outs

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:55.120
to give you odds 4
out of 47, or 8%.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:58.150
And you can see this is
the exact calculation,

00:13:58.150 --> 00:14:02.620
but it's really very close
to just multiplying by 2.

00:14:02.620 --> 00:14:04.700
So back to pot odds.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:06.550
Your break even is when EV is 0.

00:14:06.550 --> 00:14:10.710
That's a common theme that
we're going to be talking about.

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:14.090
So the bet is x
into a pot of $380.

00:14:14.090 --> 00:14:17.655
Your chance of hitting the
flush is 9 times 4%, or 36%-ish.

00:14:20.290 --> 00:14:22.400
we're assuming that we
get to see both cards.

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:25.780
Why do I think we're going
to get to see both cards?

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:29.110
Because he's all in, and
he can't bet anymore.

00:14:29.110 --> 00:14:31.540
So win percentage is 36%.

00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:34.410
Our exact win rate
is 34%, showing

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:36.370
that this is pretty close.

00:14:36.370 --> 00:14:39.140
We didn't actually need
to do any heavy math

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:41.260
to get a good ballpark number.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:45.286
So the question here is,
we're facing a bet of $370.

00:14:45.286 --> 00:14:49.020
The pot before we
face that bet is $380.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:50.810
And the question
is, should we call?

00:14:50.810 --> 00:14:53.350
Because you're not going--
you can solve the threshold

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:56.980
conceptually just to
get a resilient solution

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:58.760
set, especially when
you're doing things

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:02.040
before or after the
fact, but in real time,

00:15:02.040 --> 00:15:04.310
we're going to want a rule
for how to figure this out.

00:15:04.310 --> 00:15:06.226
So let's talk through
this one, and then we'll

00:15:06.226 --> 00:15:08.300
go through the solution
on the next side.

00:15:08.300 --> 00:15:10.660
So we have to figure out
whether to call this.

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.494
So what are we drawing to?

00:15:13.494 --> 00:15:14.660
So we're drawing to a flush.

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:18.020
So how many cards will
result in a flush here?

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:18.720
Nine, right.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:21.110
So there are nine remaining
hearts in the deck,

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:23.160
and then we get to
see one or two cards.

00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:24.510
AUDIENCE: Two cards.

00:15:24.510 --> 00:15:25.510
PROFESSOR: Yep, I agree.

00:15:25.510 --> 00:15:27.860
So we get to see two
cards because he's all in.

00:15:27.860 --> 00:15:33.730
So our chance of winning is
4% times 9, so 9%, 18%, 36%.

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:37.280
So we can call up to 36%.

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:40.340
We can contribute up to
36% of the final pot.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:46.470
So we would contribute $370 into
the final pot of 2 times this

00:15:46.470 --> 00:15:48.160
plus 1 times this.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:49.950
And just offhand,
you can calculate--

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:51.670
you can figure out
that's around 1/3,

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:55.670
because the pot is about
equal to the size of his bet.

00:15:55.670 --> 00:15:59.180
So we're contributing a
little bit less than 33%,

00:15:59.180 --> 00:16:01.280
so we know that this is
going to be a good call.

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:03.500
And that's how you would
do this in real time.

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:06.690
You'd say you're 36% to win.

00:16:06.690 --> 00:16:11.510
You're contributing 33% of the
pot, so you decide to call.

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:15.151
And that's how you would
make this decision.

00:16:15.151 --> 00:16:18.300
So let's do a couple
more examples.

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:19.900
These are all
different situations

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:21.560
where this type of
thing might come up.

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:24.820
So here's a situation where
we have asymmetrical stacks,

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:26.670
although the blinds
are the same.

00:16:26.670 --> 00:16:28.150
So we have six,
seven of diamonds.

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:30.650
I'm using the four color deck
just to make it easier to see.

00:16:33.170 --> 00:16:35.690
Something happens pre-flop
that doesn't really matter.

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:39.100
On the flop, there'
$320 in the pot.

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:40.910
He bets $150.

00:16:40.910 --> 00:16:41.987
So what we do here?

00:16:41.987 --> 00:16:43.070
So what are we drawing to?

00:16:43.070 --> 00:16:44.290
We're drawing to a straight.

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:46.167
So how many outs do we have?

00:16:46.167 --> 00:16:47.750
How many cards will
hit that straight?

00:16:47.750 --> 00:16:48.592
AUDIENCE: Eight.

00:16:48.592 --> 00:16:49.550
PROFESSOR: Eight, yeah.

00:16:49.550 --> 00:16:53.030
So we got four nines
and then four fours--

00:16:53.030 --> 00:16:54.740
will make us hit that straight.

00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:55.932
So eight outs total.

00:16:55.932 --> 00:16:57.890
So what's our chance of
winning this hand based

00:16:57.890 --> 00:16:59.510
on what we're calling here?

00:16:59.510 --> 00:17:00.890
AUDIENCE: 32%.

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:02.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah, 8%, 16%, 32%.

00:17:02.370 --> 00:17:04.530
Yep, I agree with that.

00:17:04.530 --> 00:17:08.650
So based on that,
what do we have

00:17:08.650 --> 00:17:11.630
to contribute to
stay in this hand?

00:17:11.630 --> 00:17:14.050
What percentage
of the future pot?

00:17:14.050 --> 00:17:15.702
AUDIENCE: Less than 1/3.

00:17:15.702 --> 00:17:17.410
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
something less than 1/3,

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:20.710
because if he get exactly
$320, that would be 1/3.

00:17:20.710 --> 00:17:22.859
So we know this is
way less than 1/3,

00:17:22.859 --> 00:17:25.650
and since we're 32% to
win, this is probably

00:17:25.650 --> 00:17:28.000
going to be a good call.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.780
So going through the
questions-- so we

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:32.090
have an open ended
straight draw, meaning we

00:17:32.090 --> 00:17:34.190
have eight outs because
two different cards

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:36.340
would result in the straight.

00:17:36.340 --> 00:17:39.250
Our outs are any
nine and any four.

00:17:39.250 --> 00:17:41.750
We have a 33% chance
of hitting it,

00:17:41.750 --> 00:17:43.240
and what's the correct play?

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:50.180
Call, because $150 out of $620,
where $620 is the pot plus $300

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:51.840
is 24%.

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:53.220
OK, so that wasn't bad.

00:17:53.220 --> 00:17:55.010
So those are two common draws.

00:17:55.010 --> 00:17:57.300
One was a flush draw, and
one was a straight draw.

00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:59.920
So let's go to something
a little bit different.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:02.880
So we have five
five on the button.

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:04.870
He raises into us.

00:18:04.870 --> 00:18:10.260
I call, and the flop comes
three clubs, five, ace, six.

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:11.190
He bets $200.

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:11.820
OK, cool.

00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:17.060
So this is a situation
which I'm sure a lot of you

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:18.920
may have run into recently.

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:22.730
So what hand are
we drawing to here?

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:26.986
Why do we think we're behind
if we have three fives here?

00:18:26.986 --> 00:18:30.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
two of clubs [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:30.610 --> 00:18:33.760
PROFESSOR: Yeah, he might
have a flush, certainly

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:36.490
to the point where I'm not super
comfortable with the set here

00:18:36.490 --> 00:18:39.690
knowing that it's reasonably
likely for someone

00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:42.380
to have a flush here, or even
if he doesn't have a flush

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:44.590
and we bet, he's only
going to call us really

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:47.130
if he has a flush
or a better hand.

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:49.280
So he has a flush--
what are we drawing to?

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:50.695
What beats a flush here?

00:18:50.695 --> 00:18:51.570
AUDIENCE: Full house.

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:52.736
PROFESSOR: Full house, good.

00:18:52.736 --> 00:18:53.330
What else?

00:18:53.330 --> 00:18:56.109
AUDIENCE: Four fives.

00:18:56.109 --> 00:18:57.400
PROFESSOR: Yep, four of a kind.

00:18:57.400 --> 00:18:58.997
OK, so what are our outs here?

00:18:58.997 --> 00:18:59.860
AUDIENCE: Seven.

00:18:59.860 --> 00:19:00.860
PROFESSOR: Yep, I agree.

00:19:00.860 --> 00:19:01.400
Seven outs.

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:02.152
What are they?

00:19:02.152 --> 00:19:05.030
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:19:05.030 --> 00:19:05.530
Yep.

00:19:05.530 --> 00:19:09.470
So three aces, three
sixes, one five.

00:19:09.470 --> 00:19:11.720
So we have seven outs total.

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:13.845
So what's our
chance of hitting--

00:19:13.845 --> 00:19:16.555
do we count one
or two cards here?

00:19:16.555 --> 00:19:17.465
AUDIENCE: One.

00:19:17.465 --> 00:19:18.090
PROFESSOR: One.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:18.590
Why?

00:19:21.019 --> 00:19:22.560
Because he has a
lot of chips behind,

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:25.390
and there's no way, if he's
betting this on the flop,

00:19:25.390 --> 00:19:27.839
he's giving us a free
card on the turn,

00:19:27.839 --> 00:19:29.880
unless for some reason he
thinks we have a flash,

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:32.050
but we certainly
can't count on that.

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:33.560
OK, so what did we say?

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:34.370
Seven outs.

00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:38.490
So we use 2% for the
next card, or 14%.

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:41.810
So we can call up to
14% of the future part.

00:19:41.810 --> 00:19:44.960
The future pot is going
to be $2100, $2300,

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:48.340
so we can call 14% of that.

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:52.390
So what's a good
estimate of that?

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:56.730
It's going to be more than
my 280 because 14% of $2000

00:19:56.730 --> 00:20:00.080
is $280, right?

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:02.480
So he's betting
materially less than that.

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:05.710
He's way under betting
whatever he has here.

00:20:05.710 --> 00:20:08.760
If he has a flush,
he's not protecting it.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:12.370
If he doesn't have a
flush, he's losing.

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:16.060
So this is a very common example
of a villain not protecting

00:20:16.060 --> 00:20:17.920
his hand.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:20.710
This is a situation where I
see a lot of newer players

00:20:20.710 --> 00:20:21.840
screw up.

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:24.374
They're betting so little--
they're betting little

00:20:24.374 --> 00:20:26.290
because they don't want
the other guy to fold,

00:20:26.290 --> 00:20:27.690
but they're actually
losing value

00:20:27.690 --> 00:20:30.290
because the other guy folding
here would be preferable.

00:20:30.290 --> 00:20:33.370
They should bet enough that
he either folds or he makes

00:20:33.370 --> 00:20:35.769
a wrong decision if he calls.

00:20:35.769 --> 00:20:38.060
So we're drawing to full
house or four of a kind, which

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:39.250
you guys got right.

00:20:39.250 --> 00:20:42.616
Our outs are three aces,
three sixes, and one five

00:20:42.616 --> 00:20:44.050
for seven cards total.

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:50.294
Our chance of hitting the draw
is 14%, so the correct play is?

00:20:50.294 --> 00:20:51.132
AUDIENCE: Call.

00:20:51.132 --> 00:20:52.840
PROFESSOR: Yep, the
correct play is call,

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:57.430
because he's only asking us for
to contribute 9% of that pot.

00:20:57.430 --> 00:21:00.790
Since we're 14% to win,
the chunk in that pie

00:21:00.790 --> 00:21:03.700
is bigger than the 9% chunk
that we have to contribute,

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:08.370
and the result is this $122
free that he's giving us.

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:10.840
OK, so I think this
is my last example.

00:21:10.840 --> 00:21:13.060
This one should be a
little bit more fun.

00:21:13.060 --> 00:21:15.190
So this is it.

00:21:15.190 --> 00:21:18.630
So why is this a draw
that we're looking at?

00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:20.130
We're the first one to act.

00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:23.220
Why does this matter?

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:25.955
Can anyone tell
what's going on here?

00:21:25.955 --> 00:21:27.440
AUDIENCE: Big blind [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:29.240
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
so the villain here

00:21:29.240 --> 00:21:33.340
is all in blind with that $200,
because that's the big blind.

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:39.120
So by calling here or by doing
anything, he is going all in.

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:41.910
So really it's like
he acted before us,

00:21:41.910 --> 00:21:44.460
and now we're deciding
whether we want to act.

00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:48.440
So what are we drawing to here?

00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:49.800
What are we facing?

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:52.609
What does he have
in terms of a range?

00:21:52.609 --> 00:21:53.400
AUDIENCE: Anything.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:54.520
PROFESSOR: Any two cards.

00:21:54.520 --> 00:21:57.510
And then so what
are we drawing to?

00:21:57.510 --> 00:22:00.460
In general, we're drawing
to basically anything.

00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:03.320
We're hoping that we win
some amount of the time,

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:07.110
and what percentage
do we have to win?

00:22:07.110 --> 00:22:09.440
First let's start with
what's a reasonable estimate

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:14.700
for the amount we could win,
the percentage of the time?

00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:19.760
So what are some hand versus
hand percentages that you know?

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:23.564
So what's aces versus anything?

00:22:23.564 --> 00:22:24.830
AUDIENCE: 80%.

00:22:24.830 --> 00:22:27.150
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
it's like 80% or 85%.

00:22:27.150 --> 00:22:30.360
And then if he doesn't have a
pocket pair higher than both

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:34.630
of our cards, you're generally--
even if you're dominated,

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:38.100
you're like 70/30,
and then the majority

00:22:38.100 --> 00:22:40.780
of random versus
random is between 60/40

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:43.700
in either direction.

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:46.840
So say that-- what
percentage of the time

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:51.674
do we have to win here for
this to be a good call?

00:22:51.674 --> 00:22:53.840
So what's the size of the
bet that we're facing here

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:54.881
if we're the small blind?

00:22:57.340 --> 00:23:00.010
$100, right?

00:23:00.010 --> 00:23:01.750
So we're contributing
$100 here to win

00:23:01.750 --> 00:23:04.910
a pot of $400, which is
going to be on big blind

00:23:04.910 --> 00:23:06.000
from each of us.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:10.920
So if we're more than 25% to win
here, this is a plus EV call.

00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:13.530
And I see a lot of people
screw this up for some reason,

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:19.620
but you're virtually
always ahead of 25% here.

00:23:19.620 --> 00:23:22.274
So what we're drawing
to here is anything,

00:23:22.274 --> 00:23:23.690
and our chance of
hitting the draw

00:23:23.690 --> 00:23:26.980
is we're actually about
40% versus his range.

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:31.160
And even the worst heads up
hand versus any two cards

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:34.650
is 32%, so we're really
calling blind there.

00:23:34.650 --> 00:23:38.500
We are always
ahead of his range.

00:23:38.500 --> 00:23:40.750
So the correct play is
certainly going to need a call,

00:23:40.750 --> 00:23:42.410
and the EV is like $60.

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:44.740
So if we fold this, it's
worth about $60 chips.

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:48.930
So let's talk about
implied out odds.

00:23:48.930 --> 00:23:52.990
So the solution to an
implied odds question

00:23:52.990 --> 00:23:55.280
is the number of
chips that we have

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:57.570
to win after hitting our draw.

00:23:57.570 --> 00:24:02.790
So I'm using that specific
language because for pot odds

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:06.120
the solution is whether
or not you can call,

00:24:06.120 --> 00:24:08.770
or what's the maximum
bet you can call.

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:10.270
For implied odds,
it's different.

00:24:10.270 --> 00:24:12.750
It's the number of chips
you have to win later

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:14.740
to make the call good.

00:24:14.740 --> 00:24:16.460
It's the amount of
basically dead money

00:24:16.460 --> 00:24:20.860
you need to add to the
pot after the fact.

00:24:20.860 --> 00:24:24.390
So the way that we do that is
we take a look at our percentage

00:24:24.390 --> 00:24:27.170
chance of winning--
say it's 20%--

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:31.120
and then we figure out what
size would the pot have to be

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:35.734
to make the bet we are currently
facing be 20% of that pot.

00:24:35.734 --> 00:24:37.900
So here's an example, and
we're using easier numbers

00:24:37.900 --> 00:24:40.870
here because we're
dividing by percentages.

00:24:40.870 --> 00:24:45.200
So say we have a flush
draw and we're 18% to hit.

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:51.200
If the pot is $300 and we
have a bet of $180 into us,

00:24:51.200 --> 00:24:54.890
our call is going to
be 27% of the pot.

00:24:54.890 --> 00:24:58.090
So if we had a 27% chance of
winning that would be a break

00:24:58.090 --> 00:24:59.400
even call, but we don't.

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:01.470
We have an 19%
chance of winning.

00:25:01.470 --> 00:25:03.820
So by pot odds, it
says don't call.

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:06.040
But to figure out
what the amount is

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:09.180
that we want the
pot to be, we just

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:12.180
divide that $180 by
the 18% of our odds

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:14.010
to get this $1000 number.

00:25:14.010 --> 00:25:17.830
So if the part were $1000,
we could make that call.

00:25:17.830 --> 00:25:21.680
So the solution
here is this $340

00:25:21.680 --> 00:25:24.390
difference, which
is the actual part

00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:28.120
after we call-- the difference
between that and the pot

00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:30.430
that we need to make
this call neutral.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:33.330
That's where this
$340 comes from.

00:25:33.330 --> 00:25:35.620
And it has to be in dead money.

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:37.980
It has to be money
that's added to the pot

00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:41.020
after we already hit our flush.

00:25:41.020 --> 00:25:45.930
So to visualize-- so we
need that bet of $180

00:25:45.930 --> 00:25:49.410
from the example I just
gave to be 18% of the pot.

00:25:49.410 --> 00:25:52.860
That's what makes it a good bet.

00:25:52.860 --> 00:25:55.520
As of the time that
we make the decision,

00:25:55.520 --> 00:26:00.376
our bet here represents
27% of that pot.

00:26:00.376 --> 00:26:04.220
However, if we can
increase a pot by $340,

00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:07.540
that bet would be
18% of that new pot.

00:26:07.540 --> 00:26:11.110
So that gives us the right
implied odds to make this call.

00:26:11.110 --> 00:26:14.050
And what we need to figure
out is whether this $340

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:17.020
number is realistic-- the
difference between this $1000

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:19.080
and that $660.

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:20.500
So are we following that?

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:22.439
Is that making it
easier to understand

00:26:22.439 --> 00:26:24.980
what we're trying to figure out
when we're doing implied odds

00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:25.900
question?

00:26:25.900 --> 00:26:26.787
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:26:26.787 --> 00:26:27.620
PROFESSOR: OK, cool.

00:26:27.620 --> 00:26:31.910
So I think I have two or
three examples here just

00:26:31.910 --> 00:26:34.490
to walk through that idea.

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:35.660
So here's a hand.

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:51.300
So here's a decision
we're facing,

00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:53.750
and we need to figure out
whether this is a good call.

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:55.550
So we have plenty
of chips behind.

00:26:55.550 --> 00:26:59.920
We all started with
$1000, and then we're

00:26:59.920 --> 00:27:03.110
probably not winning this hand
because we have middle pair.

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:05.630
So we're drawing to two
pair or three of a kind.

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:10.080
Our outs are these, which
are five outs total,

00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:12.830
which gives us a chance of
hitting our draw of what?

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:15.270
So do we get to see
one or two cards?

00:27:15.270 --> 00:27:16.792
AUDIENCE: One.

00:27:16.792 --> 00:27:17.500
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:19.000
We get to see one card,
because presumably he's

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:20.030
going to bet again.

00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:23.470
So we multiply by 2% to get a
10% chance of hitting the draw,

00:27:23.470 --> 00:27:27.080
and then let's go back to this.

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:30.000
So what does the pot
have to be to make

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.192
this bet 10% of the future pot?

00:27:33.192 --> 00:27:34.136
AUDIENCE: $1000.

00:27:34.136 --> 00:27:35.327
AUDIENCE: $900.

00:27:35.327 --> 00:27:36.910
PROFESSOR: Well, it
needs to be $1000,

00:27:36.910 --> 00:27:39.870
because we're contributing
$100 of some pot

00:27:39.870 --> 00:27:41.680
that we have 10% equity in.

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:43.220
So it needs to be
$1000, which means

00:27:43.220 --> 00:27:46.890
how much additional money do we
need to add after we call that?

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:54.030
So after this call it's
going to be $100, $475, $575,

00:27:54.030 --> 00:27:57.370
because we're calling $100, so
that's going to be in the pot,

00:27:57.370 --> 00:27:57.870
too.

00:27:57.870 --> 00:28:00.610
And then it's the delta
between that and $1000

00:28:00.610 --> 00:28:01.950
that we care about.

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:06.920
So it's going to be
$1000 minus $575.

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:11.330
We need to draw $425
in addition at the end.

00:28:11.330 --> 00:28:13.200
So I have a 10%
chance of hitting.

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:16.760
Our odds are 16%, meaning
we can't call it there.

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:21.060
However, if we can pull
out that $100 bet divided

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:24.760
by the 10% odds that we
need, it creates $1000 pot

00:28:24.760 --> 00:28:26.720
with the difference of $575.

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:31.120
So we need $425 more on
that after we hit our draw

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:33.767
to make that a good call,
which in that situation

00:28:33.767 --> 00:28:34.475
seems reasonable.

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:40.030
So he got $100
into a pot of $400.

00:28:40.030 --> 00:28:42.960
Presumably he'll bet like
$200 or $300 next hand,

00:28:42.960 --> 00:28:46.790
and then we can re-pop
him for anything.

00:28:46.790 --> 00:28:49.010
Even if it's a min bet,
which he'll presumably

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:51.190
be obligated to call,
especially because this

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:58.800
is a very hidden draw, we'll be
able to make this a good call.

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:01.970
So I think this is reasonably
a good call based on I

00:29:01.970 --> 00:29:06.660
think we could get $400,
$500 more at least.

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:09.609
So let's do another
one of these.

00:29:09.609 --> 00:29:12.150
So I'm going to make these all
from the same position and all

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:13.690
the pre-flop actions
the same just

00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:16.750
to make it simple to
see what's going on.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:26.680
OK, so here let's go
through the same steps.

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:28.401
So what are we drawing to here?

00:29:28.401 --> 00:29:29.442
AUDIENCE: Straight flush.

00:29:29.442 --> 00:29:32.350
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:29:32.350 --> 00:29:33.980
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
so several things.

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:36.180
So we're drawing to a straight.

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:37.250
We're drawing to a flush.

00:29:37.250 --> 00:29:39.198
We're drawing to anything else.

00:29:39.198 --> 00:29:40.910
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:29:40.910 --> 00:29:44.240
So, I would agree we're
drawing to a royal flush also.

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:47.180
And I'm going to say the
over pair might not be good.

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:49.810
One pair I wouldn't
consider a great hand,

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:54.970
especially when we're--
what were blinds here?

00:29:54.970 --> 00:29:55.740
$50, $100?

00:29:55.740 --> 00:29:59.480
So we have an m of like $50?

00:29:59.480 --> 00:30:01.110
Something like that.

00:30:01.110 --> 00:30:07.650
So I think our m-- our top
pair is not that great here,

00:30:07.650 --> 00:30:09.280
but I do think
the flush is good.

00:30:09.280 --> 00:30:11.310
Probably like a king
high flush is good,

00:30:11.310 --> 00:30:13.400
and then the straight
is good, too.

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:14.790
So how many outs
do we have here?

00:30:18.750 --> 00:30:20.730
So how many outs to the flush?

00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:21.954
AUDIENCE: Nine.

00:30:21.954 --> 00:30:24.370
PROFESSOR: Right, so we have
nine other clubs in the deck.

00:30:24.370 --> 00:30:26.294
And then how many
outs to the straight?

00:30:26.294 --> 00:30:27.090
AUDIENCE: Eight.

00:30:27.090 --> 00:30:28.090
PROFESSOR: Eight, right.

00:30:28.090 --> 00:30:30.631
So we have 17 outs, and
then how many are overlaps?

00:30:30.631 --> 00:30:32.554
AUDIENCE: Two.

00:30:32.554 --> 00:30:33.470
PROFESSOR: Two, right.

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:35.011
So let me make sure
I got that right.

00:30:35.011 --> 00:30:36.715
So 9 plus 8.

00:30:36.715 --> 00:30:37.840
17 Minus 2.

00:30:37.840 --> 00:30:38.970
Yep, 15.

00:30:38.970 --> 00:30:40.090
So we have 15 outs here.

00:30:40.090 --> 00:30:43.422
And then how many cards
are we going to see?

00:30:43.422 --> 00:30:44.320
AUDIENCE: One.

00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:46.329
PROFESSOR: We're
going to see one.

00:30:46.329 --> 00:30:47.870
I really wouldn't
estimate that we're

00:30:47.870 --> 00:30:51.050
going to see two cards, unless
someone is specifically all in.

00:30:51.050 --> 00:30:53.430
So use one card here.

00:30:53.430 --> 00:30:58.150
So we have 15 outs over
one card, so what's

00:30:58.150 --> 00:31:00.666
our percent chance of
winning on that next card?

00:31:00.666 --> 00:31:01.520
AUDIENCE: 30%.

00:31:01.520 --> 00:31:02.670
PROFESSOR: 30%, good.

00:31:06.070 --> 00:31:08.850
So what would the pot
have to be eventually

00:31:08.850 --> 00:31:11.410
to make this a good call with
our 30% chance of winning

00:31:11.410 --> 00:31:12.700
this hand?

00:31:12.700 --> 00:31:18.180
AUDIENCE: $1800?

00:31:18.180 --> 00:31:22.430
PROFESSOR: It would
be-- so I think it

00:31:22.430 --> 00:31:25.540
would be $600 divided by 30%.

00:31:25.540 --> 00:31:26.206
Right?

00:31:26.206 --> 00:31:26.830
So what's that?

00:31:26.830 --> 00:31:29.154
So $600 divided by 3/10.

00:31:29.154 --> 00:31:31.570
No, I think it's going to be
more than that, because we're

00:31:31.570 --> 00:31:34.410
going to multiply by 10/3.

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:38.110
So it's going to $6000
divided by 3, or $2000.

00:31:38.110 --> 00:31:39.960
Would you agree with that?

00:31:39.960 --> 00:31:41.770
So this pot has to
be $2000 by the end.

00:31:41.770 --> 00:31:45.110
Now, what's it going to
be when we call here?

00:31:45.110 --> 00:31:45.905
AUDIENCE: $1425.

00:31:45.905 --> 00:31:47.030
PROFESSOR: Yeah, let's see.

00:31:47.030 --> 00:31:50.140
So it's going to be $600--
his $600 plus our $600.

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:52.066
$1200 plus $275.

00:31:52.066 --> 00:31:54.200
Yeah, $1475.

00:31:54.200 --> 00:31:56.780
So how many additional
dollars do we need in the pot

00:31:56.780 --> 00:31:58.540
after hitting one of our draws?

00:31:58.540 --> 00:31:59.662
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:59.662 --> 00:32:00.620
PROFESSOR: Good, right.

00:32:00.620 --> 00:32:02.110
So I think that's right.

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:04.280
So drawing to straight or flush.

00:32:04.280 --> 00:32:06.140
Any ace, any nine,
seven other clubs

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:09.120
that aren't ace or
nine for 15 outs.

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:12.000
We are 30% to hit this.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:16.210
So right now the pot odds are
40% because he's betting $600--

00:32:16.210 --> 00:32:21.100
or we'd be contributing $600
into a total pot of $1475.

00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:24.540
We need to win an
additional $525 after it

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:25.810
to make this a good call.

00:32:25.810 --> 00:32:26.440
So that's it.

00:32:26.440 --> 00:32:28.080
So that's how you
do implied odds.

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:32.060
Just make sure you understand
what the future pot has to be,

00:32:32.060 --> 00:32:34.050
and then you can use
your own judgment

00:32:34.050 --> 00:32:37.350
for whether that's a
realistic amount to win here.

00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:40.700
I think here $500 is
totally reasonable,

00:32:40.700 --> 00:32:42.820
because he already bet $600.

00:32:42.820 --> 00:32:47.770
Even if a flush comes, he's
probably pretty obligated

00:32:47.770 --> 00:32:49.650
to make at least
another a $500 bet

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:53.020
or at least a $500
call if he checks.

00:32:53.020 --> 00:32:55.890
So I think that's good.

00:32:55.890 --> 00:32:58.290
To make it a little
simpler for you guys,

00:32:58.290 --> 00:33:01.560
I made explicit
all of the formulas

00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:06.850
that we went over for drawing,
just to help with the case.

00:33:06.850 --> 00:33:10.820
So our normal EV formula is
just-- so x is always going

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:12.270
to be what we're solving for.

00:33:12.270 --> 00:33:16.790
Our EV is just is the either
benefit or cost of the decision

00:33:16.790 --> 00:33:17.890
that we're facing.

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:21.950
It's just going to be the
combination of our win percent

00:33:21.950 --> 00:33:25.000
and loss percent and the
win amount and loss amount.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.760
How you determine pot odds
is just a decision rule.

00:33:27.760 --> 00:33:30.290
Yes or no-- do you
make this call?

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:34.350
It's just your win percentage
of the hand-- the chance

00:33:34.350 --> 00:33:36.230
you hitting your
draw, whether that's

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:40.342
greater than the call amount
divided by the pot plus 2 times

00:33:40.342 --> 00:33:42.800
the call amount, because the
bet amount and the call amount

00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:43.950
are the same thing.

00:33:43.950 --> 00:33:46.590
If it is greater, then
you make the call.

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:47.920
If it's less than, you fold.

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:52.926
Implied odds, which we
just went over-- it's

00:33:52.926 --> 00:33:54.300
going to be the
bet amount you're

00:33:54.300 --> 00:33:58.600
facing divided by your chance of
winning the hand minus whatever

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:01.890
the pot is going to be
after you make that call.

00:34:01.890 --> 00:34:03.106
I think that's it.

00:34:03.106 --> 00:34:04.480
So these are all
the formulas you

00:34:04.480 --> 00:34:06.615
need to make these decisions.

00:34:06.615 --> 00:34:08.989
You can generally remember
them when you're at the table.

00:34:08.989 --> 00:34:13.350
I think they're fairly
intuitive, and if not,

00:34:13.350 --> 00:34:15.090
they seem fairly
easy to memorize.

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:18.440
Anyway, so let's do a
