We lose if he has jack, queen.

00:39:13.172 --> 00:39:15.156
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:39:15.156 --> 00:39:18.628
If he has a jack-- he
can have a jack, queen.

00:39:18.628 --> 00:39:20.116
That's fine, but
if he has a jack,

00:39:20.116 --> 00:39:22.767
then it's the 1/2, but
if he does not have

00:39:22.767 --> 00:39:24.690
a jack, then any nine wins.

00:39:24.690 --> 00:39:25.940
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's right.

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:27.430
This is a conservative play.

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:29.262
AUDIENCE: This is
a really-- this

00:39:29.262 --> 00:39:30.640
is the worst case scenario.

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:31.931
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I would agree.

00:39:31.931 --> 00:39:35.110
If this says call, then
we're definitely calling.

00:39:35.110 --> 00:39:37.950
It's a real pain to have
aggressive estimates,

00:39:37.950 --> 00:39:39.580
and then it says
call, and you need

00:39:39.580 --> 00:39:41.496
to wonder [? why their ?]
estimates are wrong.

00:39:41.496 --> 00:39:44.550
So this gives us a
more clear example.

00:39:44.550 --> 00:39:47.900
Anyway, so the correct play
is going to be to call here.

00:39:47.900 --> 00:39:49.424
It's a little bit
difficult to see,

00:39:49.424 --> 00:39:50.840
but we're going
to say that what's

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:53.070
in the pot are all
the bets that happened

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:54.450
before he was re-raised.

00:39:54.450 --> 00:39:57.620
So that's the original
part of $1400,

00:39:57.620 --> 00:40:02.540
that one guy that bet $500 for
some reason, and then this,

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:08.890
which would be our all in
call, which was the $6275 2,

00:40:08.890 --> 00:40:10.662
because he bet that,
and we called that.

00:40:10.662 --> 00:40:11.620
This was a small blind.

00:40:11.620 --> 00:40:13.170
I don't know if you saw.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:16.560
The small blind here
just called $500

00:40:16.560 --> 00:40:19.340
and then folded when
