00:42:03.300 --> 00:42:04.124
[END PLAYBACK]

00:42:04.124 --> 00:42:05.040
PROFESSOR: Anyway, OK.

00:42:05.040 --> 00:42:05.790
So he won that.

00:42:05.790 --> 00:42:07.810
The guy, Jacobson,
I'm pretty sure

00:42:07.810 --> 00:42:10.040
ended up winning the
World Series that year.

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:12.130
OK, so we have a
bunch of be carefuls.

00:42:12.130 --> 00:42:15.110
Do not draw to a hand
that may not actually

00:42:15.110 --> 00:42:16.860
win when you hit it,
which means if you're

00:42:16.860 --> 00:42:19.890
drawing to a flush
that's not even that good

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:22.130
and maybe dominated
by another flush,

00:42:22.130 --> 00:42:25.670
you probably shouldn't count
all those as full outs,

00:42:25.670 --> 00:42:29.040
or the lower end of a straight
is really, really bad.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:31.040
It's really common for
people to draw to that

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:33.010
and then just go
broke, because they

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:35.200
think they made their
hand, but as it turns out,

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:37.780
they made the second best hand.

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:40.840
In addition, don't draw
out to a worse made hand

00:42:40.840 --> 00:42:42.372
than is already possible.

00:42:42.372 --> 00:42:43.830
So people refer to
something called

00:42:43.830 --> 00:42:47.440
a paired board, which means
two cards on the board

00:42:47.440 --> 00:42:48.315
have the same number.

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:54.180
That means that four of a kind
or full house are possible.

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:58.690
So if you're drawn to a straight
or a flush, you might not even.

00:42:58.690 --> 00:43:01.870
You might be-- drawing
dead, is what it's called.

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:04.310
You like you might be
0% to win that hand,

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:07.270
so be careful on drawing
on a paired board.

00:43:07.270 --> 00:43:10.010
In addition, do not assume
you get to see both cards.

00:43:10.010 --> 00:43:12.570
It's really common for
players to think that,

00:43:12.570 --> 00:43:14.820
OK, there are two cards left.

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:16.130
He doesn't seem too aggressive.

00:43:16.130 --> 00:43:18.046
I'll probably get to see
both cards for cheap,

00:43:18.046 --> 00:43:21.990
and then find out that
their assumptions when

00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:26.810
calling the flop ended up being
really bad and costing them EV.

00:43:26.810 --> 00:43:31.450
So very rarely does
someone check the turn.

00:43:31.450 --> 00:43:34.170
Unless the turn is
really scary, like you

00:43:34.170 --> 00:43:36.840
hit your draw obviously,
or it looks like you did,

00:43:36.840 --> 00:43:39.140
no one is was going to
give you that for free.

00:43:39.140 --> 00:43:41.170
Another thing to
be careful about

00:43:41.170 --> 00:43:43.120
is don't overestimate
how easy it

00:43:43.120 --> 00:43:45.250
is to extract additional chips.

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:48.200
It's really, really obvious
when someone hits a flush draw,

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:51.250
because there aren't that
many reasons people are going

00:43:51.250 --> 00:43:54.080
to call a bet on the flop
when there are two clubs on it

00:43:54.080 --> 00:43:58.280
and then bet when another
club hits on the turn.

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:00.460
Flushes are really
obvious and everyone

00:44:00.460 --> 00:44:02.080
is keeping an eye on that.

00:44:02.080 --> 00:44:05.490
Straights are less
obvious because a lot

00:44:05.490 --> 00:44:09.700
of different boards can have
a straight on it so they can't

00:44:09.700 --> 00:44:11.530
really just assume
that you're going

00:44:11.530 --> 00:44:14.970
to have a straight if there are
any like four cards that are

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:17.020
near each other by the turn.

00:44:17.020 --> 00:44:19.290
And sets, like when
you have a pocket pair

00:44:19.290 --> 00:44:21.760
and you hit a third of
that pair on the turn,

00:44:21.760 --> 00:44:23.140
are basically invisible.

00:44:23.140 --> 00:44:25.180
There's no way they
can put you on that.

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:27.610
So your implied odds
for sets are huge,

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:29.890
whereas your implied
odds on flush draws

00:44:29.890 --> 00:44:32.780
are very, very small.

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:36.150
In addition, on the other
end, if you have a made hand,

00:44:36.150 --> 00:44:41.510
don't bet so little to give them
the odds to reach their draw.

00:44:41.510 --> 00:44:43.630
Basically, most of
your flop and turn bets

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:46.220
should be like 2/3
of the pot just

00:44:46.220 --> 00:44:52.320
to punish them if they
want to chase their draw.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:54.030
OK, so that's it
for implied odds.

00:44:54.030 --> 00:44:56.136
So let's move on to fold equity.

00:44:56.136 --> 00:44:57.010
So here's an example.

00:45:07.810 --> 00:45:10.710
So where you guys following
what was going on in that hand?

00:45:10.710 --> 00:45:15.760
Basically, I had position
pre-flop to make this call.

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:18.450
Then on the flop I had an
open ended straight draw.

00:45:18.450 --> 00:45:20.800
He be small enough
that I should call.

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:21.920
Same thing on the turn.

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:24.270
I think he checked behind me
on the turn, and the river

00:45:24.270 --> 00:45:24.830
he checks.

00:45:24.830 --> 00:45:25.470
Why?

00:45:25.470 --> 00:45:26.920
Why is he checking
the river here?

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:28.970
So he's checking
because he's worried.

00:45:28.970 --> 00:45:30.970
He knows I'm drawing to
something because I flat

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:32.052
called, and look.

00:45:32.052 --> 00:45:33.510
I could've been
drawing to a flush,

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:34.940
and he thinks I just hit it.

00:45:34.940 --> 00:45:36.940
So this is a perfect
bluffing opportunity,

00:45:36.940 --> 00:45:41.620
because we are basically
representing a flush.

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:43.690
So the question is,
how often does this

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:46.400
have to work to be a good
bet versus just checking

00:45:46.400 --> 00:45:48.860
behind and losing nothing?

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:51.190
With bluffing, if
it's a bad bet,

00:45:51.190 --> 00:45:53.670
we're just going to lose
money most of the time.

00:45:53.670 --> 00:45:55.910
So we have to figure out,
what proportion of the time

00:45:55.910 --> 00:45:58.840
does this have to win
to make it worth it?

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:01.800
And that's what we're going
to be looking at here.

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:06.200
The concept that will give us
the value of making this bet

00:46:06.200 --> 00:46:08.800
is called fold equity.

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:11.120
So fold equity is
the value that you're

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:13.550
getting in a hand
from the likelihood

00:46:13.550 --> 00:46:15.774
that the other player
is going to fold.

00:46:15.774 --> 00:46:17.190
So with regard to
fold equity, I'm

00:46:17.190 --> 00:46:21.160
saying your showdown value,
which is this acronym here,

00:46:21.160 --> 00:46:22.290
is 0.

00:46:22.290 --> 00:46:25.460
You can't win at showdown,
which is our situation there.

00:46:25.460 --> 00:46:29.750
If he calls us, we
definitely, definitely lost.

00:46:29.750 --> 00:46:31.930
So the formula for
this is-- at least

00:46:31.930 --> 00:46:35.370
the EV formula is just-- so it's
a derivation of the normal EV

00:46:35.370 --> 00:46:36.940
formula that we always see.

00:46:36.940 --> 00:46:40.040
It's just the pot times your
chance of winning-- i.e.

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:43.540
his fold percentage--
minus the chance of losing.

00:46:43.540 --> 00:46:45.330
And you lose that
bet if you lose,

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:47.480
but your risking the
bet to win the pot.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:51.200
If we have the chance
to win after he calls,

00:46:51.200 --> 00:46:53.010
we can add another
variable where

00:46:53.010 --> 00:46:58.330
just, instead of us just losing
this bet for the amount he

00:46:58.330 --> 00:47:00.320
calls of the time,
when he calls,

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:02.792
we're going to get some
amount of EV, which is still

00:47:02.792 --> 00:47:04.500
presumably going to
be negative, but it's

00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:07.850
going to be a less negative
than just losing the entire bet.

00:47:07.850 --> 00:47:11.790
So that's the basic formula
for semi-bluffing here.

00:47:11.790 --> 00:47:16.020
Some I'm defining
bluffing is a bet

00:47:16.020 --> 00:47:18.750
where it has
positive expectation

00:47:18.750 --> 00:47:22.110
because the fold
equity is more than 0.

00:47:22.110 --> 00:47:25.410
Just this term,
just the proportion

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:27.910
of the pot that you
expect to win from him

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:33.390
folding is greater than
the weighted chance

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:34.914
of you losing that bet.

00:47:34.914 --> 00:47:37.330
That's just going to be called
a bluff, an outright bluff.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:39.870
And I differentiate
that from semi-bluffing,

00:47:39.870 --> 00:47:43.040
where this is actually
negative, where

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:44.860
if you have a 0%
chance of winning,

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:47.470
it's actually a bad bet,
because he calls you more

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:49.970
times than makes that valuable.

00:47:49.970 --> 00:47:52.100
But a semi-bluff
actually becomes

00:47:52.100 --> 00:47:55.940
positive expectation because of
your showdown win percentage.

00:47:55.940 --> 00:48:01.140
Your showdown win percentage is
sufficiently high to offset it,

00:48:01.140 --> 00:48:03.060
and this is where
the value comes from,

00:48:03.060 --> 00:48:06.000
because you have the
opportunity to steal pots,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.754
but you also the opportunity
redraw to a winning hand.

00:48:10.754 --> 00:48:12.920
And that's why in tournaments
this becomes something

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:15.419
that you're going to be doing
very often, because you're not

00:48:15.419 --> 00:48:17.670
going to always have made
hands, but you're always

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:20.320
going to have something that
could become a made hand,

00:48:20.320 --> 00:48:23.420
and that becomes good enough.

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:26.300
So how often does this have
to work to be profitable?

00:48:26.300 --> 00:48:29.150
So I'm just going to
give you a formula here.

00:48:29.150 --> 00:48:31.740
So we're betting $150
into a pot of $350 where

00:48:31.740 --> 00:48:34.340
we have no chance of
winning if he calls.

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:37.030
Our EV, which is just
taking it from that formula,

00:48:37.030 --> 00:48:41.300
is $350 times the chance we
fold minus $150, our bet,

00:48:41.300 --> 00:48:43.190
times the chance he calls.

00:48:43.190 --> 00:48:46.270
So we can solve
this for EV equals 0

00:48:46.270 --> 00:48:48.830
and then solve for fold
to get this formula.

00:48:48.830 --> 00:48:53.100
We get $150 divided by
the pot plus our bet.

00:48:53.100 --> 00:48:54.840
So this is our bet,
because the idea

00:48:54.840 --> 00:48:58.590
is that we are putting $150
into that pot for a chance

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:00.560
of winning that whole pot back.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:04.510
He won't add that $150
to the pot if we win it,

00:49:04.510 --> 00:49:05.830
so that's the idea there.

00:49:05.830 --> 00:49:07.800
So it's our bet
divided by the pot

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:12.050
after we bet to give us our
neutral EV fold percentage.

00:49:12.050 --> 00:49:14.950
So that's the chance
of him folding

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:16.510
that makes this a good bet.

00:49:16.510 --> 00:49:19.890
So I think this is pretty cool.

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:22.040
You can use this to
determine what's a good bluff

00:49:22.040 --> 00:49:24.160
and what's a bad
bluff by just saying,

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:27.460
is he going to call this
more than 1/3 of the time?

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:29.340
And just the EV
calculation, looking

00:49:29.340 --> 00:49:34.820
at using this formula to prove
that we reach a neutral EV

00:49:34.820 --> 00:49:40.590
is just 30% times this $350,
the pot minus 70%, him calling,

00:49:40.590 --> 00:49:41.500
times our bet.

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:42.781
That equals 0.

00:49:42.781 --> 00:49:45.280
And that's our quick-- I like
plugging this back into the EV

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:48.400
formula just to make
sure we messed around

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:51.110
with the variables properly.

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:52.609
So are we OK with this so far?

00:49:52.609 --> 00:49:55.150
Because we're going to move on
to something a little bit more

00:49:55.150 --> 00:49:56.790
complicated.

00:49:56.790 --> 00:49:59.510
In this one, be bet
$75 like he did before,

00:49:59.510 --> 00:50:01.640
but we are raising $150.

00:50:01.640 --> 00:50:04.230
Why?

00:50:04.230 --> 00:50:08.050
Why are we raising $150 here
rather than just calling?

00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:10.595
Yeah, because we have an
open ended straight draw,

00:50:10.595 --> 00:50:13.220
where even if he calls,
we still could win,

00:50:13.220 --> 00:50:16.340
and that fundamentally
changes what we

00:50:16.340 --> 00:50:18.960
need to make this profitable.

00:50:18.960 --> 00:50:21.110
So here, our chance
of winning is 16%.

00:50:21.110 --> 00:50:21.920
8 times 2.

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:23.420
We get to see just the river.

00:50:23.420 --> 00:50:27.560
So it's $150 into a pot of $350
where our win percent is 16%.

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:30.410
This is still our chance of
taking now the pot uncontested,

00:50:30.410 --> 00:50:33.870
and then the 1 minus f percent,
the chance that he calls,

00:50:33.870 --> 00:50:37.970
is multiplied by our
marginal EV, this 16% times

00:50:37.970 --> 00:50:39.120
winning the pot.

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:42.330
$500 is $150 $350--
$150 our bet,

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:46.510
$350, the pot--
minus $150, our bet.

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:48.440
I guess a $150 here
would be his bet,

00:50:48.440 --> 00:50:52.830
but still we have a chance
to $500 or lose $150.

00:50:52.830 --> 00:50:55.780
One of the reasons fold
equity is really hard

00:50:55.780 --> 00:50:59.110
to teach is because there's
no real intuitive way

00:50:59.110 --> 00:51:01.090
to memorize this formula.

00:51:01.090 --> 00:51:04.690
So what I did here is I
just solved for EV equals

00:51:04.690 --> 00:51:09.130
0 for our fold percentage.

00:51:09.130 --> 00:51:11.100
So we could solve this--
I just plugged this

00:51:11.100 --> 00:51:14.420
into Wolfram Alpha, and I
got the neutral fold percent

00:51:14.420 --> 00:51:19.600
is just 12%, compared
to here we need

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:22.050
to win this bluff
30% of the time,

00:51:22.050 --> 00:51:24.040
and here we need to
win 12% of the time.

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:26.220
That shows the value
of the semi-bluff here.

00:51:26.220 --> 00:51:30.420
So to check with EV, you
win $350 12% of the time,

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:34.530
and 88% of the time you
have to deal with this.

00:51:34.530 --> 00:51:37.650
So that shows, at
least intuitively,

00:51:37.650 --> 00:51:39.590
what the value is
but let's see if we

00:51:39.590 --> 00:51:44.530
can figure out exactly
how important this win

00:51:44.530 --> 00:51:45.650
percentage is.

00:51:45.650 --> 00:51:51.520
So we're going to have
to use calculus for this.

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:55.140
So when we graph this
formula, we see a clear trend,

00:51:55.140 --> 00:51:56.590
and it would be intuitive.

00:51:56.590 --> 00:52:00.250
When your showdown win
percentage goes up,

00:52:00.250 --> 00:52:03.410
the amount you need
him to fold goes down.

00:52:03.410 --> 00:52:07.110
If you win 0% of the time,
he needs to fold a lot,

00:52:07.110 --> 00:52:09.030
but then if you win
some amount of the time,

00:52:09.030 --> 00:52:12.280
he only needs to fold a
smaller amount of the time.

00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:13.980
So that's what this
thing is saying.

00:52:13.980 --> 00:52:15.813
And there are a couple
of interesting points

00:52:15.813 --> 00:52:17.550
on this graph which
I want to point out.

00:52:17.550 --> 00:52:21.020
So what's this point here?

00:52:21.020 --> 00:52:25.980
It's our break even fold
percentage for having a 0 EV.

00:52:25.980 --> 00:52:30.420
So the idea is, if he
folds, how you read this is,

00:52:30.420 --> 00:52:32.200
if we have a 16%
chance of winning

00:52:32.200 --> 00:52:35.330
if we're drawing to an open
ended straight for one card,

00:52:35.330 --> 00:52:38.160
if he folds more than
12% percent of the time,

00:52:38.160 --> 00:52:41.586
if we're in anywhere in
this area, it's positive EV

00:52:41.586 --> 00:52:44.220
and for anywhere
down here it's not.

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:46.310
So that's how we're
reading this graph here.

00:52:46.310 --> 00:52:49.470
So what about this point here?

00:52:49.470 --> 00:52:53.130
It's a complete bluff because
we have 0% chance of winning,

00:52:53.130 --> 00:52:55.310
and you recognize this 30%.

00:52:55.310 --> 00:52:59.510
It's from all the way back here.

00:52:59.510 --> 00:53:02.967
It's when we had a
0% chance of winning.

00:53:02.967 --> 00:53:04.800
So that's that point
up there, which I think

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:08.497
is pretty interesting,
but it gets even cooler.

00:53:08.497 --> 00:53:09.580
OK so that's what that is.

00:53:09.580 --> 00:53:14.090
It's our $150 divided
by $150 plus $350, which

00:53:14.090 --> 00:53:16.900
is our formula for determining
what our break even

00:53:16.900 --> 00:53:19.100
fold percentage is
for a complete bluff.

00:53:19.100 --> 00:53:22.470
That's our 30% here,
but check this out.

00:53:22.470 --> 00:53:24.790
So what is this number?

00:53:24.790 --> 00:53:26.790
It's our pot odds break even.

00:53:26.790 --> 00:53:28.700
It's the size of the
bet that we could

00:53:28.700 --> 00:53:32.560
call if he was betting
to make us neutral EV.

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:33.850
That's what this 23% is.

00:53:33.850 --> 00:53:37.750
It's our $150 divided by
the pot after our call.

00:53:37.750 --> 00:53:41.980
What that means is, if
he folds 0% of the time,

00:53:41.980 --> 00:53:44.830
I, similarly, did he
just bet, and then we

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:46.230
have the option to call.

00:53:46.230 --> 00:53:47.930
That makes a 0 EV.

00:53:47.930 --> 00:53:52.237
So this graph connects all
of those variables for us,

00:53:52.237 --> 00:53:54.320
and that lets us derive
something very interesting

00:53:54.320 --> 00:53:56.080
with regard to implied odds.

00:53:56.080 --> 00:53:58.890
We could just figure out
how implied odds impacts

00:53:58.890 --> 00:54:01.662
our fold percentage by
looking at this secant line

00:54:01.662 --> 00:54:03.120
and coming up with
a good estimate.

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:04.746
So let me work through
this graph, talk

00:54:04.746 --> 00:54:06.453
through what we're
seeing here, because I

00:54:06.453 --> 00:54:07.720
think this is really cool.

00:54:07.720 --> 00:54:15.290
So to be clear, this blue line
is our neutral fold percentage,

00:54:15.290 --> 00:54:19.060
and then this slope
is-- it's the derivative

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:23.920
of how much of a bonus
we get to fold percentage

00:54:23.920 --> 00:54:25.920
for every 1% win rate.

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:29.390
So for each additional one
out, each additional 2%,

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:33.087
he needs the fold 3% less
for us to break even there.

00:54:33.087 --> 00:54:34.420
That's what this is telling you.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:38.090
When you have a 10%
chance of winning,

00:54:38.090 --> 00:54:44.080
you just reduce
this amount by 15%.

00:54:44.080 --> 00:54:46.040
You multiply it by the
one and a half slope.

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:48.320
Although it undershoots
it by a little bit,

00:54:48.320 --> 00:54:50.200
it gives you a very,
very close estimate

00:54:50.200 --> 00:54:55.330
to using these implied
odds in real time.

00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:57.350
And then so I went
ahead and figured out,

00:54:57.350 --> 00:55:00.250
OK, so that's for a
specific bet size.

00:55:00.250 --> 00:55:03.330
How's it work if we look at
for a much bigger bet or a much

00:55:03.330 --> 00:55:04.160
smaller bet?

00:55:04.160 --> 00:55:06.300
I found something
really interesting.

00:55:06.300 --> 00:55:09.700
When the bet becomes-- when
we go towards infinity,

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:11.780
the partial derivative is 2.

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:16.450
You only get as much of a bonus
as 2 times your win percentage.

00:55:16.450 --> 00:55:19.160
So each additional out
gives you like 8% percent

00:55:19.160 --> 00:55:23.300
reduced in break even
for fold percentage.

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:25.550
And then when your
bet approaches 0,

00:55:25.550 --> 00:55:27.740
you only get a 1% decrease.

00:55:27.740 --> 00:55:30.530
So these are our bounds.

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:34.740
For a pot size bet, it's
1.5% percent your bonus,

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:37.920
and regardless,
you know your bonus

00:55:37.920 --> 00:55:40.030
is going to be between
1 and 2, at least

00:55:40.030 --> 00:55:43.810
in terms of the average
across win percentages.

00:55:43.810 --> 00:55:45.180
That's what we discovered here.

00:55:45.180 --> 00:55:46.850
And what this is
letting us do is

00:55:46.850 --> 00:55:48.920
it's less letting us
create a quick rule that

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:51.170
implements implied odds.

00:55:51.170 --> 00:55:55.680
So to go over what
these rules exactly are,

00:55:55.680 --> 00:55:58.300
let's back up to
a complete bluff.

00:55:58.300 --> 00:56:02.160
So our fold needed
is just the bet

00:56:02.160 --> 00:56:06.280
divided by the pot
and the bet combined.

00:56:06.280 --> 00:56:09.130
If you want to bet the
exact size of the pot, which

00:56:09.130 --> 00:56:13.180
isn't that bad for a bluff, you
only need to win half the time.

00:56:13.180 --> 00:56:16.870
And then you can, if you want,
scale linearly down to 0.

00:56:16.870 --> 00:56:20.360
You could just say, all
right, if I bet half the pot,

00:56:20.360 --> 00:56:22.264
I have to win 25% of the time.

00:56:22.264 --> 00:56:23.180
It's a little bit off.

00:56:23.180 --> 00:56:26.135
It's like 33% of the time,
but it's not that bad.

00:56:26.135 --> 00:56:27.510
So this gives you
a very easy way

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:30.240
to determine when you
should bluff or not,

00:56:30.240 --> 00:56:32.035
and obviously there's
a bit of judgment

00:56:32.035 --> 00:56:33.910
because you've got to
figure out whether this

00:56:33.910 --> 00:56:36.700
is a reasonable number, but
it gives you idea of you

00:56:36.700 --> 00:56:40.030
don't need to win that
bluff 80% of the time.

00:56:40.030 --> 00:56:43.650
And then when you actually
have a chance to redraw to win,

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:46.720
it becomes even
more interesting.

00:56:46.720 --> 00:56:51.410
So in general, when
you have a draw,

00:56:51.410 --> 00:56:53.085
your value is higher
because you still

00:56:53.085 --> 00:56:54.870
have a chance to win the hand.

00:56:54.870 --> 00:56:57.690
And in general, you're going
to see very rarely will people

00:56:57.690 --> 00:57:03.000
actually make complete bluffs,
because they would prefer--

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:04.990
the chance of you winning
the hand at the end

00:57:04.990 --> 00:57:08.700
materially makes
your value better.

00:57:08.700 --> 00:57:11.900
So a simple assumption
is just each 1%

00:57:11.900 --> 00:57:16.730
your showdown increases you
decrease your fold percentage

00:57:16.730 --> 00:57:18.300
by 1.5%.

00:57:18.300 --> 00:57:20.940
And your fold percentage are
going to be much, much smaller.

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:24.180
They're going to be like
15% to 20-ish percent,

00:57:24.180 --> 00:57:25.470
somewhere in that range.

00:57:25.470 --> 00:57:27.780
So decreasing that
by 5% actually makes

00:57:27.780 --> 00:57:31.630
you quite a bit more
likely to win, or at least

00:57:31.630 --> 00:57:34.407
have a positive
expectation decision.

00:57:34.407 --> 00:57:35.990
And when we talk
about pre-flop, which

00:57:35.990 --> 00:57:37.614
is going to be nothing
but figuring out

00:57:37.614 --> 00:57:41.120
semi-bluffing
opportunities, we're

00:57:41.120 --> 00:57:45.530
going to be heavily
using this type of thing.

00:57:45.530 --> 00:57:47.625
So let's do some examples.

00:58:07.240 --> 00:58:09.000
OK, so what is going on here?

00:58:12.440 --> 00:58:15.570
So just to watch
that again-- so it

00:58:15.570 --> 00:58:18.470
looks like the villain
raised something pre-flop.

00:58:18.470 --> 00:58:19.770
I had position, so I called.

00:58:24.740 --> 00:58:29.100
And then he showed weakness
for three straights in a row,

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:31.750
I don't know what he has,
but it seems to be worth

00:58:31.750 --> 00:58:33.020
taking a stab at it.

00:58:33.020 --> 00:58:34.590
So then what
proportion of the time

00:58:34.590 --> 00:58:38.060
does this step have to work
to make it a good bluff?

00:58:38.060 --> 00:58:40.750
So is this going to be
bluff or a semi-bluff?

00:58:40.750 --> 00:58:41.470
AUDIENCE: Bluff.

00:58:41.470 --> 00:58:41.780
PROFESSOR: Bluff.

00:58:41.780 --> 00:58:42.615
Why?

00:58:42.615 --> 00:58:43.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:43.770 --> 00:58:47.480
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I
barely beat the board.

00:58:47.480 --> 00:58:52.030
I think my 10 high plays,
but only very close.

00:58:52.030 --> 00:58:56.250
So there's no way he can call
this with the worse hand.

00:58:56.250 --> 00:58:58.590
So the question is,
how often does this

00:58:58.590 --> 00:59:00.110
have to work to be valuable?

00:59:00.110 --> 00:59:03.560
Which is a very common question
you might ask yourself.

00:59:03.560 --> 00:59:05.310
So do you remember how
to figure this out?

00:59:09.770 --> 00:59:13.000
So the formula is
going to be this.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:16.210
It's just the bet divided
by the pot plus the bet.

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:18.440
So difference between this
and the pot odds formula

00:59:18.440 --> 00:59:19.850
is one bet.

00:59:19.850 --> 00:59:23.790
Pot odds formulas is pot
plus two bets, ours and his.

00:59:23.790 --> 00:59:25.860
This formula is just
the pot plus our bet

00:59:25.860 --> 00:59:29.560
only, because he
never adds his bet in.

00:59:29.560 --> 00:59:31.740
So to figure out our
chance of winning here,

00:59:31.740 --> 00:59:34.080
let's just go to this one.

00:59:34.080 --> 00:59:35.280
We just do what?

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:37.150
We take this side of
our bet and divide it

00:59:37.150 --> 00:59:39.420
by this plus this number.

00:59:39.420 --> 00:59:41.458
So we add those
together, it's what?

00:59:41.458 --> 00:59:43.200
$625.

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:47.380
So we'd just take $250 divided
by $625, which is what?

00:59:47.380 --> 00:59:48.250
It's 40%.

00:59:48.250 --> 00:59:50.630
So this needs to work 40%
of the time to be valuable.

00:59:50.630 --> 00:59:53.520
So it's actually
not as interesting

00:59:53.520 --> 00:59:54.520
as I would have guessed.

00:59:54.520 --> 00:59:57.120
This needs to work a
pretty big amount of time.

00:59:57.120 --> 00:59:59.980
And given that he's
shown so much weakness,

00:59:59.980 --> 01:00:02.170
he's probably guessing that
we're probably buffing.

01:00:02.170 --> 01:00:06.710
But anyway, if he
calls 25% of the time,

01:00:06.710 --> 01:00:11.220
does that make that
a good bet or not?

01:00:11.220 --> 01:00:13.570
Yes, because that
means he folds 75%

01:00:13.570 --> 01:00:16.230
of the time, which
is more than our 40%.

01:00:16.230 --> 01:00:17.840
So that makes that a good bet.

01:00:17.840 --> 01:00:21.230
And just to plug into
the EV formula, what

01:00:21.230 --> 01:00:24.680
is our value from this bluff
if our estimate is right here

01:00:24.680 --> 01:00:27.240
that he calls 25% of the time?

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:30.890
It's $200, so the pot is what?

01:00:30.890 --> 01:00:34.390
I think the pot is $400 here.

01:00:34.390 --> 01:00:37.942
So that makes sense to
me that 75% of the time

01:00:37.942 --> 01:00:40.400
we're going to take down that
pot, so it's worth about $200

01:00:40.400 --> 01:00:40.900
to us.

01:00:43.740 --> 01:00:45.979
So that's it.

01:00:45.979 --> 01:00:47.020
Let's do another example.

01:01:03.130 --> 01:01:04.850
OK, so what's going on?

01:01:04.850 --> 01:01:07.710
Something happened
on the flop, and then

01:01:07.710 --> 01:01:08.680
what are we doing here?

01:01:08.680 --> 01:01:09.769
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:09.769 --> 01:01:10.560
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:01:10.560 --> 01:01:15.210
So we're betting $450
into a pot of $775.

01:01:15.210 --> 01:01:19.690
So the question is,
is this a good bet?

01:01:19.690 --> 01:01:21.270
Should we have done this?

01:01:21.270 --> 01:01:23.530
And we're going to be
facing these decisions

01:01:23.530 --> 01:01:26.130
all throughout the tournament.

01:01:26.130 --> 01:01:32.960
So this one is going to be kind
of complicated, but not really.

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:34.840
Let's see what we can
piece together for now.

01:01:34.840 --> 01:01:37.605
So what's our chance of
winning this one at showdown?

01:01:40.270 --> 01:01:41.924
So we have 16%
chance of winning.

01:01:41.924 --> 01:01:42.840
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:45.750 --> 01:01:49.590
PROFESSOR: It's hard to--
I prefer not counting--

01:01:49.590 --> 01:01:52.810
you can proportion partial
outs to whatever you think

01:01:52.810 --> 01:01:55.270
your real chance of winning
if you hit that is-- say,

01:01:55.270 --> 01:01:56.676
that's worth 1/3 of an out.

01:01:56.676 --> 01:01:58.550
But in terms of being
conservative and making

01:01:58.550 --> 01:02:00.280
this simple, we
could just say, let's

01:02:00.280 --> 01:02:02.100
say we have to hit
the straight to win,

01:02:02.100 --> 01:02:04.350
although you can consider
yourself having a little bit

01:02:04.350 --> 01:02:06.180
more equity if
you just say maybe

01:02:06.180 --> 01:02:10.290
I'll win if I hit
a 10 or something.

01:02:10.290 --> 01:02:15.260
So we're betting for $450
into this pot of $775.

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:18.540
So we know we have a 16%
chance of winning this hand

01:02:18.540 --> 01:02:20.360
if we are called.

01:02:20.360 --> 01:02:25.330
If we have no percent
chance of winning the hand

01:02:25.330 --> 01:02:27.710
if we are called, what
proportion of the time

01:02:27.710 --> 01:02:30.300
do we need him to fold
to make this good?

01:02:30.300 --> 01:02:32.610
$450 divided by $1225.

01:02:32.610 --> 01:02:38.310
That $1225 is going
to be $450 plus $775.

01:02:38.310 --> 01:02:39.170
Is that right?

01:02:39.170 --> 01:02:40.970
What was the bet?

01:02:40.970 --> 01:02:47.230
Yeah, $450 plus $775 $1225.

